post_text:
A message from our Superintendent, Dr. Sturz -

As a reminder, as was stated in the July 31 letter to parents, if you do not intend to send your child to school due to COVID-19 related concerns you must inform the district in writing . You can send either an email or a letter to your building principal. If you have any questions regarding the Reopening Plan please contact your building principal to discuss them. Stay safe and be well.

Thanks,
Dr. Don Sturz
#LookForTheAwesome #VS24

Dear Parents/Guardians:
We have been informed that a family member of a staff who works at the R.W. Carbonaro School has self-reported having tested positive for COVID-19. This has not been confirmed by the Department of Health.
These are very challenging times and we are all understandably anxious and concerned. The most important things to do are to take recommended precautions, stay informed with accurate information and try to remain calm. The health and safety of our students, staff and community are our foremost priority as we attempt to help prevent the spread of the virus.
Sincerely,
Dr. Don Sturz
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
A reminder that Kindergarten Registration for the 2020/2021 school year will take place this week on three separate dates at each of our schools. #LookForTheAwesome

Tuesday, February 4th
Robert W. Carbonaro School
50 Hungry Harbor Road
9:00 AM - 11:00 AM

Wednesday, February 5th
William L. Buck School
75 Horton Avenue
9:00 AM - 11:00 AM

Thursday, February 6th
Brooklyn Avenue School
24 Brooklyn Avenue
9:00 AM - 11:00 AM

If you have a child or know of a child who will turn age 5 on or before December 1, 2020, he/she will be eligible to enter Kindergarten in September 2020. Please contact the child's home school in order to obtain a registration packet, which must be completed and notarized prior to the registration date for which you are scheduled. You can find a Registration packet on our website: www.valleystreamschooldistrict24.org

Once your child is registered, you will receive further information regarding Kindergarten Orientation. If you have any questions, please contact the building principal of your home school.

post_text:
William L. Buck School First Graders are raising funds to help support the kids of St. Jude Children's Research Hospital. They have a goal to raise as much as possible for the kids of St. Jude. But they need your help.

Will you help them support St. Jude by donating today?

How your support helps:

Families never receive a bill from St. Jude for treatment, travel, housing or food â€” because all a family should worry about is helping their child live.

St. Jude is working to drive the overall survival rate for childhood cancer to 90%, and we won't stop until no child dies from cancer.

St. Jude freely shares the discoveries it makes, and every child saved at St. Jude means doctors and scientists worldwide can use that knowledge to save thousands of more children.

Please visit their St. Jude page to make a donation. Once you donate, please share it on Facebook and Twitter with a challenge to support the kids of St. Jude. You'll help families and patients around the world.

Thank you for your support!

Please donate through the link below!

http://events.stjude.org/WLBschool

post_text:
This week our BAS 2nd-grade students took advantage of the warm weather to read outside. Studies show reading and learning outside decreases stress and promotes mindfulness. After returning to the media center, they discussed as a class how spending some time reading outside made them feel.

Our BAS 4th-grade students are working on their GIF animation project using Piskel.com. (Our students really have so many talents!)

The BAS 5th-grade students are beginning the last stage of their comic projects. They are taking pictures of their panels and creating a comic video using Animoto.com. #LookForTheAwesome

Our BAS 4th-grade students are working on their GIF animation project using Piskel.com. (Our students really have so many talents!)

The BAS 5th-grade students are beginning the last stage of their comic projects. They are taking pictures of their panels and creating a comic video using Animoto.com. #LookForTheAwesome

post_text:
This past week in BAS, our first-grade classes took part in a Dot Day Makerspace lesson. After reading the book "The Dot" by Peter Reynolds, the students were put into groups and challenged to build a house or tower using only index cards and dot stickers. The students had to use their hands, work together, and use engineering skills to build their structures.

Our upper elementary students continued working on their comic book projects. This week the students have learned about character development and are thinking deeply about the characters for their own comic strips.

Our fifth-grade students expanded and connected their comic character knowledge to doodle art and mindfulness. The students learned about the relaxing qualities doodling has on our minds and bodies. The students worked in groups to create doodles on large paper that will be turned into a Doodle Board. Students will be able to come to the media center to rest their bodies and minds for a few minutes by coloring on the Doodle Board. #DotDay #LookForTheAwesome

post_text: Our summer program students are hard at work, improving VS24's school community! During their first week of the summer program, the class set out on a mission to solve a micro or small problem in our school. They walked around the school grounds paying close attention to their surroundings. While walking, they recorded their observations and then took a survey on Google Forms to determine how they wanted to make a difference. After they identified the problem: not a lot of wildlife around the school, sustained inquiry: research groups set out to find reasonable and sustainable ways to draw more wildlife, they came to their solution: a birdbath!! Thank you, students and Ms. Gallo for creating this beautiful birdbath for everyone to enjoy. Come check out their project (and hang with our new bird friends) at WLB! ðŸ¦ #LookForTheAwesome
